Introduction

Hello! Here I present a brief recounting of the COVID-19 cases and deaths in the U.S. from March 2020 to December 23rd 2021, adding a timeline of some relevant events from those two years. This data was taken from the CDC website, and can be found there.

First we need to load the necessary packages and the data. I will be using a select number of packages from the tidyverse and svglite.

library(knitr)
library(lubridate)
library(readr)
library(magrittr)
library(dplyr)
library(stringr)
library(ggplot2)
library(svglite)

The CDC data on COVID-19 can be found here saved here as covid, and the timeline is part of the online CDC museum.

As this data loads in, I also make sure the timeline is processed into Date format.

Day Event
2020-01-20 First reported US case.
2020-03-15 US Begins to shut down.
2020-03-17 Moderna Trial Begins.
2020-03-26 Senate Passes CARES Act.
2020-03-28 US FDA issues EUA to allow anti-malarial drugs to treat COVID-19.
2020-04-13 White House announces U.S. will cease funding the WHO.

I also parse through the longitudinal data into date format. To label the important dates in the timeline, I also convert the POSIXct into a numeric.

covid_parsed <- covid %>% mutate(submission_date = strptime(submission_date,
                                                     format = "%m/%d/%Y"),
                          created_at = strptime(created_at,
                                                format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M:%S %p"))

timeline_parsed <- as.numeric(ymd(timeline$Day))

Summarizing and plotting the data

The data are ready to be summarized. There are many potential data-points to visualize, but I was particularly interested in new and total counts of cases and deaths, to really understand the tremendous impact of the pandemic.

covid_parsed <- covid_parsed %>%
    group_by(state, week = floor_date(submission_date, unit = "week")) %>%
    summarize(med_cases_new = median(new_case),
              med_deaths_new = median(new_death),
              med_cases_tot = median(tot_cases),
              med_deaths_tot = median(tot_death)) %>% ungroup()

I’ve made a ggplot2 function which will make it easier to plot each plot. I don’t include any geoms or aesthetics that we might want to change for each plot.

timeplot <- ggplot(data = covid_parsed, aes(x = as.Date(week),
                          group = as.factor(state),
                          fill = as.factor(state))) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "magma") +
  xlab("") + ylab("") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(hjust = 1, angle = 45),
    axis.line = element_line(color = "black", size = 1, lineend = "square"),
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major.y = element_line(color = "lightgray", size = 1),
    legend.position = "none"
    )

Here is the first plot I generate, looking at the median new cases for every week.

timeplot + labs(title = "Median Weekly Cases") +
  geom_area(aes(y = med_cases_new)) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = str_to_upper("%b %Y")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "K", scale = 1e-3),
                       expand = c(0, NA)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = timeline_parsed, col = "black", lwd = 0.5)

ggsave("MedianTotalCases_Tutorial.svg", device = "svg", height = 5, width = 8)

We can save this for later as an scalable vector graphic, or svg file, before importing it into Illustrator to work on it some more.

This second plot does not include the vertical lines looking at events.

timeplot + labs(title = "Median Total Cases") +
  geom_area(aes(y = med_cases_tot)) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = str_to_upper("%b %Y")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "M", scale = 1e-6),
                       expand = c(0, NA))

Instead of plotting the weekly cases, this shows the cumulative number of total cases over time. This is actually an imperfect measure due to counting any person that was or is COVID-19 positive, which can happen multiple times. To take a more accurate look at the tragedy that COVID-19 precipitated, we can take a look at cumulative deaths over time, since there is a far lower chance of any double counting.

timeplot + labs(title = "Median Total Deaths") +
  geom_area(aes(y = med_deaths_tot)) +
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 month", date_labels = str_to_upper("%b %Y")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "K", scale = 1e-3),
                       expand = c(0, NA))

Finally after annotating our first plot in a vector graphics program (I used Illustrator) we are able to get a fully annotated plot.
